ISI Wants INDIA Out OF AFGHANISTAN: Time For US To Stem<br/><br/>No one believed it when India cried hoarse, accusing Pakistan of “doing all” to keep India out of Afghanistan. But now- its a reputed American think tank who has said it- that Pakistan’s ISI wants the Taliban to be influential enough within the Afghan government so that it can keep India out. James Dobbins from the Rand Corporation and his colleagues recently visited Pakistan and interacted with ISI officials He is quoted as saying, “What the Pakistanis told us when we were in Islamabad – is that they share our interest in bringing peace, that they want the Afghan Taliban out of Pakistan and back into Afghanistan, but not in a position of dominating the country.”
<br /><br />“But they would like the Taliban sufficiently influential within the Afghan government so that, on the one hand, they have an incentive to stop interfering and get out of Pakistan … And, secondly, that they preserve Pakistani interests in Afghanistan, the principal of which is to keep the India’s RAW away from the Pakistani border-away from dissident elements within Pakistan, particularly in Baluchistan”, Mr Dobbins added.
<br /><br />Dobbins continues, “The other narrative is that they want a sympathetic force to dominate the Afghan government, for the same reason: to prevent it from becoming allied with India, which has far more to offer in terms of economic assistance and commerce”. “They’re going to continue to support the Taliban with that kind of outcome, so that the situation reverts to what they found in the 1990s, and then they possibility can put their clients back in power in Kabul, and in the rest of the country”, he said referring to the interaction with ISI officials in Pakistan, including representatives of the civilian government.
<br /><br />Though President Obama is determined to get out of Afghanistan by 2014, resolution of this war is getting tangled up in one of the world's most stubborn rivalries : India versus Pakistan. Citing India's influence in Afghanistan as its top concern, Pakistan is becoming increasingly critical to any military or diplomatic progress in the war if India is involved in any manner! It's a concern that Washington has to somehow manage.
<br /><br />Some current and retired Pakistani officials have hinted that as both the war and the peace efforts become more and more difficult, Washington and its Afghan allies might have todo more to reassure Islamabad that India won't play a major role in a future Afghan settlement. Its main worry, one might say bordering on paronia, is about having to defend both its eastern and western borders, if India and Afghanistan grew too close! It also alleges that India uses its consulates in Afghanistan to conduct espionage, stirring up anti-government forces in Pakistan's frontier regions. Officials mutter darkly about upto 19 Indian &quot;consulates&quot; based in sensitive border areas, as if it were fact (and the fact is that there are only three).
<br /><br />If we analyse India's role in the Afghanistan conflict, we will see that it was the Americans who propped us upto occupy centre-stage. But why-we shall see in the subsequent lines :-
<br /><br />India is More Important than Afghanistan- Newsweek's Fareed Zakaria warns that Obama shouldn't alienate India,(which he says is a key long-term ally), just for the sake of short-term gain in Afghanistan. He writes, &quot;Obama must keep in mind that South Asia is a tar pit filled with failed and dysfunctional states, save for one long-established democracy of 1.2 billion people that is the second-fastest-growing major economy in the world, a check on China's rising ambitions, and a natural ally of the United States. The prize is the relationship with India.The booby prize is governing Afghanistan.&quot;
<br /><br />India Should Lead Afghan Development- Forbes' Marshall M. Bouton and Alyssa Ayres call India &quot;the country best positioned to increase civilian assistance.&quot; India, like the US, has been victim to Afghanistan-based terrorism and badly wants the Taliban out”. India, they write, could provide key financial and cultural support while the US and NATO do the military `mopping up’. Obama should urge India to &quot;take on a more committed leadership role in Afghanistan's future and in building Afghan civil society.&quot;
<br /><br />Don't Abuse India- The Boston Globe's Nicholas Burns frames the challenge as &quot;how to balance a short-term need for progress in Afghanistan and Pakistan without losing sight of our equally important long-term ambitions with India.&quot; He writes, &quot;Influential Indians complain the Obama administration is diminishing America’s prior strategic priority on India, to avoid antagonizing regional rivals Pakistan and China.&quot; He suggests leading an India-Pakistan detente. &quot;India must be more sensitive to Pakistani concerns over its involvement in Afghanistan, while Islamabad should finally prosecute the terrorists responsible for the Mumbai attacks.&quot;
<br /><br />India Wants US Presence in Afghanistan- Juan Cole reports that India wants US to stay in Afghanistan. He says Manmohan Singh &quot;pressured&quot; Obama &quot;not to execute a hasty withdrawal from Afghanistan as that would have catastrophic results for the security and stability not only of Pakistan, but also for the whole of South Asia.&quot;
<br /><br />Pakistan Wants India Détente- The Washington Post's Ahmed Rashid argues that we in USA should lead the talks between Pakistan and India. &quot;The Pakistan military's primary interest in a regional strategy was that Americans would help restart Indo-Pakistan talks on Kashmir and other disputes that ceased after the terrorist attack on Mumbai, and negotiating a reduction of India's influence in Kabul, which Pakistan now blames for a host of ills (some imagined, some real).&quot;
<br /><br />History is witness to how the Afghan region has been simmering with conflicts for nearly three decades- first the Soviet occupation, then the Taliban regime (1994-2001), and to top it all-Osama bin Laden, who had made it his base. Many militants, including foreign mercenaries were then trained in his camps to go back and wage jihad in Kashmir. But in 2001, the Taliban was toppled, and a Northern Alliance–dominated government took its place. India educated Hamid Karzai then became President. India stepped in with multimillion-dollar reconstruction projects, which Pakistan resented, but couldn’t prevent -as it neither had the technology nor the money to help-embroiled as it was, with a war in its backyard-America’s GWOT-that had just hit the  road- post the 9/11 debacle !
<br /><br />So, in conclusion, we must realize that until Pakistan feels secure in its relationship with India, it will continue to believe that its interests are best advanced through clandestine support of the Taliban and other elements that destabilize Afghanistan. The way to win that trust, would be to resolve the festering Kashmir issue. Such a resolution would bring other dividends as well-deprived of the Kashmir cause, Islamist militancy within Pakistan would lose support. A strong diplomatic initiative will go a long way toward convincing local stakeholders that the US is not only committed to eliminating extremism, but that it is also invested in regional development. Subsequent peace would then free up vital trade routes to Central Asia-enriching Afghanistan, by opening Indian markets to Pakistani products and resources.
